<p>We assume the following: </p>  <pre><code>class a {   public static $foo = 'bar'; } class b {   public $classname = 'a'; } $b = new b(); </code></pre>  <p>Is it somehow (curly braces etc.) possible to access $foo directly without generating an "unexpected :: (T_PAAMAYIM_NEKUDOTAYIM)":</p>  <pre><code>$b-&gt;classname::$foo //should result in "bar" not in an "unexpected :: (T_PAAMAYIM_NEKUDOTAYIM)" </code></pre>  <p>I know and use the following workaround:</p>  <pre><code>$c = $b-&gt;classname; $c::$foo; </code></pre>  <p>but I would like to know if it exists another nice way to do access $foo directly.</p>